lass=m><span class=title> Failover... Tech question for Tigole....</span><hr size=1> Hey Tig..<br>
<br>
Has anyone at Blizzard possibly considered that instead of patching all the servers at once, that each server has a failover?  In other words they patch one server, request for everyone to log out and log back in, and when they do they are on the freshly patched server?  Then they proceed to patch the initial server?  ie:  No downtime.  <br>
<br>
I know this works well in most IT communities when you cannot have downtime for server maintenance, backups etc etc.  I don't see why something like this couldn't work in a MMORG environment. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub114.ezboard.com/blegacyofsteel43089.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kaylum>Kaylum</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#ffffff>(11/23/02 8:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub114.ezboard.com/flegacyofsteel43089general.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3606.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> ...</span><hr size=1> most likely because you would risk losing anything that happend from the time they began patching the other server until the point you logged into it.<br>
<br>
even assuming that characters are stored seperately it would totally depend on how other info is stored.<br>
<br>
EQ for example could not use this type of system: corpses among other things are stored zone server side. while players current equip is stored on a character server. creating a duped world than patching it than allowing a copy of the character to log onto it would allow someone to loot their corpse multiple times. and thats just one complication off the top of my head.<br>
<br>
for the record this was actually attempted by EQ OPs and no reasonable solution for it was found; it created several very easy expliots and their only solution would have been to risk wiping characters accidently.<br>
